### 2. Java Basic Questions They Will Ask

Because your project is in Java, they will test basics too.

---

**Q. What is OOP? Explain with example from your project.**

> "OOP stands for Object Oriented Programming. It has 4 pillars:
>
> **Encapsulation** — hiding internal data. In our project the Item class has private fields. Nobody accesses them directly. They use getters and setters generated by Lombok.
>
> **Inheritance** — one class gets properties of another. Our ItemRepository extends JpaRepository and inherits all database methods like save, findById, findAll.
>
> **Abstraction** — hiding complexity. ItemService interface defines WHAT operations exist. ItemServiceImpl defines HOW they work. Controller only knows the interface, not the implementation.
>
> **Polymorphism** — one interface, multiple implementations. ItemService interface can have multiple implementations. Spring injects the correct one automatically."

---

**Q. What is an Interface? Why did you use it in Service layer?**

> "An interface defines a contract — it says WHAT methods exist but not HOW they work. We created ItemService interface and ItemServiceImpl class that implements it. Benefits:
> - Controller depends on the interface, not the implementation
> - Easy to swap implementations later
> - Easy to mock in unit tests
> - Follows the principle — program to interface not implementation"

---

**Q. What is the difference between Abstract Class and Interface?**

```
Interface                          Abstract Class
─────────────────────────────      ─────────────────────────────
All methods are abstract           Can have both abstract and
by default                         concrete methods

No constructor                     Can have constructor

A class can implement              A class can extend only
multiple interfaces                one abstract class

Used for: defining a contract      Used for: sharing common code
```

---

**Q. What is Exception Handling in Java?**

> "Exception handling is a way to deal with runtime errors gracefully. We use try-catch blocks or throw exceptions. In our project we created custom exceptions like ItemNotFoundException. When an item is not found in the database we throw this exception. The GlobalExceptionHandler catches it and returns a clean 404 JSON response to the client."

---

**Q. What is the difference between Checked and Unchecked Exception?**

```
Checked Exception                  Unchecked Exception
─────────────────────────────      ─────────────────────────────
Must be handled or declared        No need to handle or declare

Checked at compile time            Checked at runtime

Extends Exception                  Extends RuntimeException

Example: IOException               Example: NullPointerException
         SQLException                       ItemNotFoundException
                                            (our custom exception)
```

> "In our project all custom exceptions extend RuntimeException so they are unchecked. Spring handles them through GlobalExceptionHandler."

---

**Q. What is the difference between == and .equals()?**

> "== compares memory addresses — checks if two variables point to the exact same object in memory. .equals() compares the actual content of the objects. For example two different String objects with value 'Electronics' would return false for == but true for .equals(). Always use .equals() for comparing object values."

---

**Q. What are Collections in Java?**

> "Collections are data structures that hold multiple objects. Common ones:
> - List — ordered, allows duplicates. ArrayList is most common
> - Set — unordered, no duplicates. HashSet is most common
> - Map — key-value pairs. HashMap is most common
>
> In our project we return List<ItemDTO> from service methods when fetching multiple items."

---

**Q. What is Optional in Java?**

> "Optional is a container that may or may not contain a value. It avoids NullPointerException. In our project itemRepository.findById(id) returns Optional<Item>. We call .orElseThrow() on it — if the value is present it returns it, if not it throws ItemNotFoundException. This is cleaner than checking if the result is null."

---

**Q. What is the difference between ArrayList and LinkedList?**

```
ArrayList                          LinkedList
─────────────────────────────      ─────────────────────────────
Uses array internally              Uses doubly linked list

Fast random access by index        Slow random access

Slow insert/delete in middle       Fast insert/delete anywhere

Uses less memory                   Uses more memory

Best for: reading data             Best for: frequent insert/delete
```

---

**Q. What is HashMap?**

> "HashMap stores data as key-value pairs. Each key is unique. You can get a value instantly by its key. In our GlobalExceptionHandler we use Map<String, String> to collect validation errors — field name as key, error message as value."

---

**Q. What is String, StringBuilder, StringBuffer?**

```
String          → Immutable. Every change creates new object
                  Use when string rarely changes

StringBuilder   → Mutable. Changes happen on same object
                  Not thread safe. Use in single thread

StringBuffer    → Mutable. Thread safe version of StringBuilder
                  Slower because of synchronization
```

