### 3. Database Questions They Will Ask

---

**Q. What is a Primary Key?**

> "Primary key is a column that uniquely identifies each row in a table. It cannot be null and cannot have duplicate values. In our items table, the id column is the primary key. It auto-increments — MySQL automatically assigns 1, 2, 3 to new rows."

---

**Q. What is a Foreign Key?**

> "A foreign key is a column in one table that refers to the primary key of another table. In our inventory table, item_id is a logical foreign key that refers to the id in items table. It creates a relationship between the two tables."

---

**Q. What is the difference between WHERE and HAVING?**

> "WHERE filters rows before grouping. HAVING filters groups after GROUP BY. WHERE works on individual rows. HAVING works on aggregated results like COUNT, SUM, AVG."

---

**Q. What is an Index in database?**

> "An index is like the index at the back of a book. Instead of reading every page to find a word, you go to the index and find the page directly. Database index works the same way — it speeds up SELECT queries. The downside is it slows down INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE because the index also needs to be updated."

---

**Q. What is normalization?**

> "Normalization is organizing database tables to reduce redundancy and improve data integrity. The main forms are:
> - 1NF — each column has atomic values, no repeating groups
> - 2NF — no partial dependencies on primary key
> - 3NF — no transitive dependencies
> Our tables follow normalization — each table has one job and data is not repeated."

---

**Q. What is the difference between INNER JOIN and LEFT JOIN?**

```
INNER JOIN → Returns rows that have matching values in BOTH tables
             If no match → row is excluded

LEFT JOIN  → Returns ALL rows from left table
             If no match in right table → NULL values for right columns
```

---

**Q. What is a Transaction in database?**

> "A transaction is a group of SQL operations that either all succeed or all fail together. This follows ACID properties:
> - Atomicity — all or nothing
> - Consistency — database stays in valid state
> - Isolation — transactions don't interfere with each other
> - Durability — committed data is permanent
> In our project @Transactional annotation handles this automatically."

---

### 4. Questions About Your Thought Process

These are behavioral questions about decisions you made.

---

**Q. Why did you create separate DTO and Model classes? Why not use one class for both?**

> "Using the same class for both database and API would create problems. First, you might expose sensitive database fields to clients. Second, you cannot add API-specific validation like @NotBlank on a database entity without mixing concerns. Third, if the database structure changes you don't want the API to break automatically. Keeping them separate gives full control over both independently."

---

**Q. Why did you use Builder pattern in your project?**

> "Builder pattern makes object creation cleaner and more readable especially when a class has many fields. Instead of a constructor with 5 parameters where you might mix up the order, builder lets you set each field by name. Lombok's @Builder generates this automatically. For example Item.builder().name('Mouse').category('Electronics').build() is much clearer than new Item(null, 'Mouse', null, 'Electronics', null)."

---

**Q. Why did you use constructor injection instead of field injection with @Autowired?**

> "Constructor injection through @RequiredArgsConstructor is preferred because:
> - Dependencies are explicit and visible
> - Fields can be final which prevents accidental reassignment
> - Easier to write unit tests — you can pass mock objects directly to constructor
> - Object is always in a complete valid state after creation
> Field injection with @Autowired hides dependencies and makes testing harder."

---

**Q. How would you handle if the database is down?**

> "In the current project the service would throw an exception and return a 500 error. In a production system I would add:
> - Connection pooling with HikariCP to reuse connections efficiently
> - Retry mechanism to retry failed database operations
> - Circuit breaker pattern using Resilience4j to stop hammering a failing database
> - Fallback responses so the application degrades gracefully instead of completely failing"

---

### 5. Scenario Based Questions

These test your practical thinking.

---

**Q. A user sends a request to create an item but forgets to include the category field. What happens?**

> "The request body is converted to ItemDTO. The @Valid annotation triggers Bean Validation. The @NotBlank annotation on the category field detects it is blank. Spring throws MethodArgumentNotValidException. Our GlobalExceptionHandler catches it and returns HTTP 400 Bad Request with this response:
> ```json
> {
>   "success": false,
>   "message": "Validation failed",
>   "data": {
>     "category": "Category is required"
>   }
> }
> ```
> The service and database are never even touched."

---

**Q. A user sends a GET request for item id 500 but it doesn't exist. What happens?**

> "The controller calls itemService.getItemById(500). The service calls itemRepository.findById(500). The database finds no row with id 500 and returns an empty Optional. The .orElseThrow() triggers and throws ItemNotFoundException with message 'Item not found with id: 500'. GlobalExceptionHandler catches it and returns HTTP 404 Not Found with the message."

---

**Q. What happens if someone calls your API without a JWT token?**

> "The JwtAuthFilter runs before the request reaches the controller. It checks the Authorization header. If the header is missing or the token is invalid, the filter blocks the request and returns HTTP 401 Unauthorized. The controller, service, and database are never touched."

---

**Q. Two people update the same item at exactly the same time. What happens?**

> "In our current implementation the last write wins — whoever saves last overwrites the other. To handle this properly in production we would use Optimistic Locking. Add a @Version annotated field to the entity. Every update increments the version. If two updates happen simultaneously, the second one will fail with OptimisticLockException because the version it read is now outdated. The client would then retry."

